<dl id="n36208b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36208b">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36208b"> 208(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Moreman <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36208b"><li>FW 534.14 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36208b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36208b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36208b">MS BL 47484b-429</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:168 <a name="rBd14" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36208b">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Mormonism.]</font> The word &ldquo;<mark>Mormon</mark>&rdquo; as given in the Century Dictionary is from a Greek word meaning &ldquo;bugbear&rdquo;, and in zo&ouml;logy it is the name of several animals, including the baboon. But Joseph Smith didn&apos;t know this. His own explanation was that since &ldquo;mo&rdquo; is the Egyptian word for good, by a simple addition of &ldquo;more&rdquo; or &ldquo;mor&rdquo;, the contraction, we get the word &ldquo;Mormon&rdquo;, which literally means &ldquo;more good&rdquo;. <small> Charles W. Ferguson, <a name="CFCT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CFCT"><cite title="source">The Confusion of Tongues</cite></a> (1928; rpt. May 1929) 372</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
